{{Infobox NRHP | name =Traveler's Rest (Montana) | nrhp_type =nhl | image = Traveler's Rest State Park view of mountains 1 20121228.JPG | caption = Countryside at Travelers Rest | nearest_city= [[Lolo, Montana]] | coordinates = {{coord|46|44|20|N|114|04|50|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Montana#USA | area = | built =1805 | architect= | architecture= | designated_nrhp_type= October 9, 1960<ref name=nhlsum>{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=305&ResourceType=Site |title=Traveler's Rest (Montana) |accessdate=November 27, 2011|work=National Historic Landmark Program|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref><ref name=redesig>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nhl/designations/Lists/MT01.pdf|format=PDF |title=Traveler's Rest |accessdate=November 27, 2011|work=National Historic Landmarks Program|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> | added = October 15, 1966<ref name=nrhp>{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natregsearchresult.do?fullresult=true&recordid=68 |title=Traveler's Rest |accessdate=November 27, 2011|work=National Register of Historic Places|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> | governing_body = Private | refnum=66000437<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|version=2010a|dateform=mdy}}</ref> }}
'''Traveler's Rest''' was a stopping point of the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]], located about one mile south of [[Lolo, Montana]]. The expedition stopped from September 9 to September 11, 1805, before crossing the [[Bitterroot Mountains]], and again on the return trip from June 30 to July 3, 1806. Traveler's Rest is at the eastern end of the [[Lolo Pass (Idaho–Montana)|Lolo Trail]].<ref name=trail>{{cite web|url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/lewisandclark/site28.htm|title=Travelers Rest Montana|date=February 22, 2004|accessdate=November 27, 2011|work=Survey of Historic Sites and Buildings|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> It was declared a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1960 and added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1966.<ref name=nhlsum/><ref name=nrhpinv2>{{citation|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Travelers Rest|url={{NHLS url|id=66000437}} |format=pdf|date=June 14, 1976 |author=Blanche Higgins Schroer and Ray M. Mattison |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NHLS url|id=66000437|title=Accompanying 8 photos, from 1971, 1975 and undated.|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(1.94&nbsp;MB)}}</ref> The boundaries were subsequently revised, and mostly lie within the {{convert|51|acre|ha|adj=on}} '''Traveler's Rest State Park''', which is operated by the Montana Fish, Wildlife & Parks. Significant archeological findings made in 2002, including latrine sites with traces of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] and fire hearths, make this the only site on the [[Lewis and Clark National Historic Trail]] that has yielded physical proof of the explorers' presence.<ref name=arch>{{cite web|url=http://m.visitmt.com/CMS/MobiRenderContent.aspx?contentGroupID=18963&p=params=&#124;&#124;12373&#124;&#124;|title=Travelers' Rest State Park|accessdate=November 27, 2011|work=Visit Montana|publisher=Montana Office of Tourism}}</ref> Records made by Lewis and Clark often spell "Traveler's" [[American and British English spelling differences#Doubled consonants|as "Traveller's"]].<ref name=nrhpinv2/> This spot is largely unchanged from the days of Lewis and Clark.<ref name=trail/> From this location, Lewis and Clark split up to explore Montana during their return trip, not reuniting until they reached [[New Town, North Dakota|Sanish, North Dakota]].<ref name=split>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/lewisandclark/tra.htm|title=Traveler's Rest|accessdate=November 27, 2011|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>
At the time of landmark designation in 1960, the exact location of the expedition's campsite was unknown. Boundaries were formalized on December 12, 1983. Subsequent investigations revealed that errors had been made in setting the boundaries of the landmark. Detailed historical and scientific investigations resulted in a 55-page request for boundary corrections, submitted on May 10, 2004, and approved on March 21, 2006.<ref name=redesig/><ref name=redes2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/20060428.HTM|title=Weekly List of Actions Taken on Properties|date=April 21, 2006|accessdate=November 27, 2011|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> A new road and bridge were built in 2006.<ref name=nhlsum/>
After departing here in 1806, Lewis' part of the expedition traveled to what is now the [[Alice Creek Historic District]].<ref name="mdf">{{cite web|url=http://www.montanadiscoveryfoundation.org/Alice_Creek.pdf|title=Alice Creek/Lewis & Clark Pass Lewis & Clark History on the Helena National Forest|publisher=Montana Discovery Foundation|format=PDF|accessdate=March 18, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218060201/http://montanadiscoveryfoundation.org/Alice_Creek.pdf|archivedate=December 18, 2010|df=}}</ref>
